  "diary": "Woke to that perfect grey-light quiet this morning—the kind where everything feels slower. Watered the plants with my coffee steaming nearby, just let myself sit with it for a minute before heading out. The drive to Fremont was smooth enough, rain tapping on the windshield like a rhythm section.\n\nThe workshop felt like exactly where I needed to be today. Something about the rain on that old roof, the smell of fresh-cut wood, the focus of detail work—it all lined up right. Grabbed something warm at Molly Moon's around midday, just enough to break it up. Spent the afternoon sanding, really getting into the grain of this custom piece. My hands knew what to do.\n\nTexted Maya later about her first week—felt good to check in. Sketched out more of the bookshelf design while listening to some music, and the ideas just kept flowing. By the time evening rolled around, I felt that good tired, the kind where you know you actually made something.",
  "thought_process": "The rain and grey sky actually helped my focus today rather than dragging me down. I think it's because I stayed in my element—the workshop is designed for days like this. The SR-520 closure didn't touch me since I'm heading to Fremont, not crossing the lake, so I just let the weather settle me instead of stress me. I prioritized deep work in the morning when my hands were freshest, broke it up with a warm meal, then came back to detail work when precision mattered less. Reaching out to Maya felt important; I've been in my own projects a lot lately. Sketching the bookshelf design felt like play, which is how I know I'm in a good headspace. The day had a natural rhythm to it, and I rode that instead of fighting it.",
